The hierarchy reel showed you two of the four pillars of object-oriented design: abstraction and inheritance. This reel covers the other two, encapsulation and polymorphism, because together they are what make objects safe to use and flexible to extend.

Start with encapsulation. The idea is simple: hide your state, and expose only a safe interface to reach it. Look at the Account class. It takes an initial Int, and inside it declares a private var called bal. That private keyword is the whole point. Outside code cannot read bal, cannot write bal, cannot even see that it exists. The balance is locked away.

So how does anyone use it? Through the interface you choose to expose. Def balance simply returns bal. Now here is a lovely Scala detail. To a caller, balance looks exactly like a field access. They write account dot balance. They have no idea whether balance is stored as a val or computed by a def. That is the uniform access principle, and it means you can start with a simple stored value and later swap in a computed one without breaking a single caller.

Next, def deposit takes an Int and returns Unit. Before it touches the balance, it calls require, which checks that the amount is positive and throws if it is not. Then it adds to bal. This is the real reward of encapsulation: because bal is private, every change to it flows through deposit, so your invariant, the balance only moves by positive amounts, is enforced in exactly one place. Nobody can reach around your rules.

Scala gives you finer control than just public and private. Protected def audit is visible to subclasses but not to the outside world. And private, in square brackets bank, means visible anywhere inside the bank package, but nowhere else. You can dial the exact boundary you want.

One more encapsulation note. When you write a case class, like Point with x and y, those constructor parameters become public vals automatically. They are readable, and because the case class is immutable, they can never change after construction. So for plain data you get safe, read-only access with zero boilerplate, no getters to write at all.

Now the second pillar: polymorphism. The word means many shapes, and in object-oriented Scala it shows up as dynamic dispatch. Picture a value a, whose declared type is Animal. You call a dot sound. But Animal is abstract; it has no sound of its own. So which sound actually runs? The answer is decided at runtime, by the real object behind that reference. If a is really a Dog, you get woof. If it is a Cat, you get meow. If it is a Cow, you get moo. One call site, many possible implementations, chosen by the runtime type. That is dynamic dispatch.

Let's see it pay off in code. You make a list, pets, declared as List of Animal, and you fill it with a Dog and a Cat. The list does not care about the concrete types; it just knows they are all Animals. Now call pets dot map of sound. Scala walks the list, and for each element it dispatches to that element's own sound, giving you back the list with woof and then meow. The same single expression handled two different types correctly.

This leads to the principle worth carrying with you: program to the abstraction, not to the concrete type. Look at the describe method. It accepts any Animal and builds a string from the animal's name and its sound. Notice that describe never mentions Dog or Cat. It speaks only to the Animal abstraction. Which means the day you add a new subtype, say a Bird, describe works on it instantly, with no changes. You wrote the code once, against the interface, and every present and future subtype just slots in.

So that is the pair. Encapsulation draws a boundary: private state inside, a safe interface outside, with your invariants guarded in one place. Polymorphism then lets callers work against that interface without knowing or caring which concrete type sits behind it. Hide what varies, expose what stays stable, and let the runtime pick the right behavior. That is the heart of object-oriented design in Scala.
